<div class="patternContent"><div class="patternTopic"> <h1><a name="Tue_Afternoon_Exercise_Using_OSG"></a> Tue Afternoon Exercise - Using OSG Security Tools </h1>
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Introduction"></a> Introduction </span></h2>
In this session you will learn how to use the OSG security tools.
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Your_certificate"></a> Your certificate </span></h2>
<p />
On <pre>
osg-ss-glidein.chtc.wisc.edu
</pre>
you should have you certificate in:<pre>
~/.globus/
</pre>
<p />
The certificate can be in one of the two formats: <ul>
<li> <code>usercert.p12</code> - This is the format Web browsers usually rely on. It contains both the public and the private part of your certificate.
</li> <li> <code>usercert.pem</code> + <code>userkey.pem</code> - This is the preferred format for the Grid environment.<br>The first file contains only the public part, while the second one contains only the private key.
</li></ul> 
<p />
<strong>Note:</strong> Make sure any file containing the private key is only readable by you.
<p />
You can convert between them by using: <ul>
<li> p12 to pem <pre class="screen">
cd ~/.globus
touch usercert.pem userkey.pem
chmod go-rwx userkey.pem
chmod go-wx usercert.pem
# Will ask for the passwd
openssl pkcs12 -clcerts -nokeys -in usercert.p12 -out usercert.pem
# Will ask for the passwd, and will ask for a 2nd passwd for the key file... use the same
openssl pkcs12 -nocerts -in usercert.p12 -out userkey.pem
</pre>
</li> <li> pem to p12 <pre class="screen">
cd ~/.globus
touch usercert.p12
chmod go-rwx usercert.p12
openssl pkcs12 -export -in usercert.pem -inkey userkey.pem -out usercert.p12
</pre>
</li></ul> 
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Looking_into_the_certificate"></a> Looking into the certificate </span></h2>
<p />
You can peek at the content of the certificate, using <a href="http://www.openssl.org/docs/apps/x509.html" target="_top">openssl</a>. 
It is installed on most Linux systems by default.
<p />
Try it out.<pre class="screen">
openssl x509 -text -in ~/.globus/usercert.pem -noout
</pre>
What do you see?
<p />
PS: We used the <code>-text</code> flag to get the complete output, but there are many useful ones as well.
I particularly like <code>-subject</code>; it prints out just your name, as encoded in the certificate.
<p />
Note: I have also used the <code>-noout</code> flag; this tells openssl to stick to the human readable output.
<p />
<div class="twistyPlugin twikiMakeVisibleInline">  <span id="twistyIdEducationAfricaGridSchoolTueExOSGSec1show" class="twistyStartHide twistyTrigger twikiUnvisited twistyInited0"><a href="#"><img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/toggleopen-small.gif" border="0" alt="" /><span class="twikiLinkLabel twikiUnvisited">Advanced</span></a> </span> <span id="twistyIdEducationAfricaGridSchoolTueExOSGSec1hide" class="twistyStartHide twistyTrigger twikiUnvisited twistyHidden twistyInited0"><a href="#"><img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/toggleclose-small.gif" border="0" alt="" /><span class="twikiLinkLabel twikiUnvisited">Hide advanced</span></a> </span>  </div><!--/twistyPlugin twikiMakeVisibleInline--> <div class="twistyPlugin"><div id="twistyIdEducationAfricaGridSchoolTueExOSGSec1toggle" class="twistyStartHide twistyContent twikiMakeHidden twistyInited0">
One of the things you can see, is that the cert was issued by DOEGrids CA.
<p />
The CA public certificates are pre-installed in <code>/etc/grid-security/certificates/</code>.<br>
Each CA has a set of files, with *.0 being the certificate.
<p />
The files are encoded using a SSL-internal scheme. You can find the right name under the your certificate "CRL Distribution" section.
<p />
Run openssl against the DOEGrids certificate.
<p />
<div class="twistyPlugin twikiMakeVisibleInline">  <span id="twistyIdEducationAfricaGridSchoolTueExOSGSec2show" class="twistyStartHide twistyTrigger twikiUnvisited twistyInited0"><a href="#"><img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/toggleopen-small.gif" border="0" alt="" /><span class="twikiLinkLabel twikiUnvisited">For the lazy</span></a> </span> <span id="twistyIdEducationAfricaGridSchoolTueExOSGSec2hide" class="twistyStartHide twistyTrigger twikiUnvisited twistyHidden twistyInited0"><a href="#"><img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/toggleclose-small.gif" border="0" alt="" /><span class="twikiLinkLabel twikiUnvisited">Hide lazy section</span></a> </span>  </div><!--/twistyPlugin twikiMakeVisibleInline--> <div class="twistyPlugin"><div id="twistyIdEducationAfricaGridSchoolTueExOSGSec2toggle" class="twistyStartHide twistyContent twikiMakeHidden twistyInited0">
<pre class="screen">
openssl x509 -text -in /etc/grid-security/certificates/1c3f2ca8.0  -noout
</pre>
</div></div> <!--/twistyPlugin--> 
<br>
<p />
What do you see?
</div></div> <!--/twistyPlugin--> 
<br>
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Creating_a_proxy"></a> Creating a proxy </span></h2>
<p />
As mentioned in the lecture, you will often need a proxy.
<p />
To create a proxy, use =grid-proxy-init=<pre class="screen">
cd ~/.globus
# either one will work
grid-proxy-init -cert ~/.globus/usercert.p12 -key ~/.globus/usercert.p12 -out ~/.globus/userproxy.pem -valid 12:0
grid-proxy-init -cert ~/.globus/usercert.pem -key ~/.globus/userkey.pem -out ~/.globus/userproxy.pem -valid 12:0
</pre>
<p />
Now look into it with openssl.
<div class="twistyPlugin twikiMakeVisibleInline">  <span id="twistyIdEducationAfricaGridSchoolTueExOSGSec3show" class="twistyStartHide twistyTrigger twikiUnvisited twistyInited0"><a href="#"><img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/toggleopen-small.gif" border="0" alt="" /><span class="twikiLinkLabel twikiUnvisited">For the lazy</span></a> </span> <span id="twistyIdEducationAfricaGridSchoolTueExOSGSec3hide" class="twistyStartHide twistyTrigger twikiUnvisited twistyHidden twistyInited0"><a href="#"><img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/toggleclose-small.gif" border="0" alt="" /><span class="twikiLinkLabel twikiUnvisited">Hide lazy section</span></a> </span>  </div><!--/twistyPlugin twikiMakeVisibleInline--> <div class="twistyPlugin"><div id="twistyIdEducationAfricaGridSchoolTueExOSGSec3toggle" class="twistyStartHide twistyContent twikiMakeHidden twistyInited0">
<pre class="screen">
openssl x509 -text -in ~/.globus/userproxy.pem  -noout
</pre>
</div></div> <!--/twistyPlugin--> 
<br>
What do you see?
<p />
Another tool you can use to look at a proxy is =grid-proxy-info=<pre class="screen">
grid-proxy-info -file ~/.globus/userproxy.pem
</pre>
Try it out.
<p />
<div class="twistyPlugin twikiMakeVisibleInline">  <span id="twistyIdEducationAfricaGridSchoolTueExOSGSec4show" class="twistyStartHide twistyTrigger twikiUnvisited twistyInited0"><a href="#"><img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/toggleopen-small.gif" border="0" alt="" /><span class="twikiLinkLabel twikiUnvisited">Advanced</span></a> </span> <span id="twistyIdEducationAfricaGridSchoolTueExOSGSec4hide" class="twistyStartHide twistyTrigger twikiUnvisited twistyHidden twistyInited0"><a href="#"><img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/toggleclose-small.gif" border="0" alt="" /><span class="twikiLinkLabel twikiUnvisited">Hide advanced</span></a> </span>  </div><!--/twistyPlugin twikiMakeVisibleInline--> <div class="twistyPlugin"><div id="twistyIdEducationAfricaGridSchoolTueExOSGSec4toggle" class="twistyStartHide twistyContent twikiMakeHidden twistyInited0">
<p />
One obvious thing to change is the proxy lifetime. Try the changing the <code>-valid</code> option.
<p />
You can also change the location of the proxy. We have been using the explicit <code>-out</code> option in <code>grid-proxy-init</code> and the <code>-file</code> opetion in <code>grid-proxy-info</code>.
You can set the <code>X509_USER_PROXY</code> variable instead.<br>
Try deleting your proxy (<strong>not the certificate</strong>) and recreating it with a different name.
</div></div> <!--/twistyPlugin--> 
<br>
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Creating_a_VOMS_extended_proxy"></a> Creating a VOMS-extended proxy </span></h2>
<p />
As explained during the lecture, OSG requires VOMS attributes to authorize you at Grid sites.
<p />
Creating a VOMS-extended proxy is very similar to creating a regular proxy; you just must use a different tool.
<p />
The tool to use is <code>voms-proxy-init</code>. You will also need to tell the tool what VO are you from (i.e. <code>osgedu</code>)<pre class="screen">
cd ~/.globus
# either one will work
voms-proxy-init -cert ~/.globus/usercert.p12 -key ~/.globus/usercert.p12 -voms osgedu -out ~/.globus/userproxy.pem -valid 12:0 -hours 12
voms-proxy-init -cert ~/.globus/usercert.pem -key ~/.globus/userkey.pem -voms osgedu -out ~/.globus/userproxy.pem -valid 12:0 -hours 12
</pre>
<p />
Try it out and look at the result with openssl.
<p />
What do you see?
<p />
Now try it with the VOMS-specific tool; =voms-proxy-info=<pre class="screen">
voms-proxy-info -file ~/.globus/userproxy.pem -file
</pre>
<p />
<div class="twistyPlugin twikiMakeVisibleInline">  <span id="twistyIdEducationAfricaGridSchoolTueExOSGSec5show" class="twistyStartHide twistyTrigger twikiUnvisited twistyInited0"><a href="#"><img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/toggleopen-small.gif" border="0" alt="" /><span class="twikiLinkLabel twikiUnvisited">Advanced</span></a> </span> <span id="twistyIdEducationAfricaGridSchoolTueExOSGSec5hide" class="twistyStartHide twistyTrigger twikiUnvisited twistyHidden twistyInited0"><a href="#"><img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/toggleclose-small.gif" border="0" alt="" /><span class="twikiLinkLabel twikiUnvisited">Hide advanced</span></a> </span>  </div><!--/twistyPlugin twikiMakeVisibleInline--> <div class="twistyPlugin"><div id="twistyIdEducationAfricaGridSchoolTueExOSGSec5toggle" class="twistyStartHide twistyContent twikiMakeHidden twistyInited0">
You may have noticed I have added also the <code>-hours</code> option; this sets the validity of the VOMS attributes. The attributes lifetime and the proxy lifetime are indeed completely independent.
<p />
Try also the <code>-chain</code> option.<br>
What do you see?
</div></div> <!--/twistyPlugin--> 
<br>
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Submitting_a_Grid_job"></a> Submitting a Grid job </span></h2>
<p />
While you will likely never need to submit Grid jobs yourselves, it is still a good idea to know how to do it.
<p />
The 5 OSG sites you have access to are: <ul>
<li> the local pool (Wisconsin) - <code>osg-ss-ce.chtc.wisc.edu:2119/jobmanager-condor</code>
</li> <li> UNL - <code>red.unl.edu:2119/jobmanager-condor</code>
</li> <li> UCSD - <code>osg-gw-2.t2.ucsd.edu:2119/jobmanager-condor</code>
</li> <li> Chicago - <code>uct2-gk.mwt2.org:2119/jobmanager-condor</code>
</li> <li> Oklahoma - <code>osgitb1.nhn.ou.edu:2119/jobmanager-condor</code>
</li></ul> 
<p />
Let's run as simple job:<pre class="screen">
export X509_USER_PROXY=~/.globus/userproxy.pem
globus-job-run osg-gw-2.t2.ucsd.edu:2119/jobmanager-condor /usr/bin/id
</pre>
<p />
Try another site, too.
<p />
<strong>Note:</strong> <code>globus-job-run</code> is a very primitive tool, and you should use it for testing only. It will not scale past a few jobs.
<p />
-- <a href="/bin/view/Main/RobQ" class="twikiLink">RobQ</a> - 30 Jul 2012</div><!-- /patternTopic-->
